<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec_collisions2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Collision Exercises</title>
	
	<activity>
	<title>Bumper Cars</title>
	<statement>
	<p>
		
	</p>
<p>Two bumper cars collide with each other and get tangled together.  Car 1 (<m>m_1</m>) moves north at <m>v_1</m>.  Car 2 (<m>m_2</m>) moves south at <m>v_2</m>.</p>
<p>
	Case 1: Initially, car 1 (<m>100 \mathrm{~kg}</m>) moves north at <m>4 \mathrm{~m/s}</m> and car 2 (<m>200 \mathrm{~kg}</m>) moves south at <m>3 \mathrm{~m/s}</m>.
</p>
<ol marker="A)">
	<li>
		<p>
			Draw a momentum vector diagram for the situation.
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<p>
			Find the final velocity of the cars.
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<p>
			Determine the initial and final kinetic energies of the cars.
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<p>
			Compare the total kinetic energy before and after the collision.
		</p>
	</li>
</ol>
<p>
	Case 2: Initially, car 1 (<m>100 \mathrm{~kg}</m>) moves north at <m>4 \mathrm{~m/s}</m> and car 2 (<m>200 \mathrm{~kg}</m>) moves south.  Both end at rest.
</p>
<ol marker="A)">
	<li>
		<p>
			Draw a momentum vector diagram for the situation.
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<p>
			Find the initial velocity of car 2.
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<p>
			Determine the initial and final kinetic energies of the cars.
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<p>
			Compare the total kinetic energy before and after the collision.
		</p>
	</li>
</ol>
</statement>
</activity>

<activity>
	<title>Energy and Collisions</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
			
		</p>
		<p>
			A small rock (mass <m>m</m>) is moving to the right on a frictionless table with speed <m>v</m>.  It hits a second rock (mass <m>M</m>) that is initially at rest on the table.  The rocks do not stick together.
		</p>
	</introduction>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Do you think momentum is conserved during this interaction?  If so, for what system is it conserved?
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Do you think energy is conserved during this interaction?  If so, for what system is it conserved?
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				A reasonable objective for this situation is to try to find the speed of each rock after the collision.  This can be complicated, so do not try it yet.
			</p>
			<p>
				What special cases do you think might be worth considering in this situation?  Try to come up with at least two.
			</p>
			<p>
				For each special case you came up with, determine the final speed of each rock.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				The final speeds of the rocks are given by: <me>v_m=\frac{m-M}{m+M}v</me><me>v_M=\frac{2m}{m+M}v</me>
				Evaluate these expressions in the special cases you came up with previously.  Were your predictions correct?
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Determine the total kinetic energy of the system both before and after the collision.  Was kinetic energy conserved during this collision?  Why or why not?
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	
</activity>
<activity>
	<title>The Firework</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
			
		</p>
		<p>
			A firework is moving to the right with speed <m>v</m> when it explodes into two pieces with equal mass (<m>m/2</m>).  Right after the explosion, the first piece is moving backward with speed <m>v</m>.
		</p>
	</introduction>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Sketch a momentum vector diagram.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>Calculate the velocity of the other piece.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Determine the change in the system's kinetic energy.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
</activity>
	
</section>